">
                                            <!-- Header -->
                                            <h2>2. Common Terms and Equatio=
ns
											</h2>
											<hr>
											<h3>Standard Deviation</h3>
											 <br>
										=09
											 <div class=3D"row">
											                                          =20
												<div class=3D"col-lg-6">
													=09
                                                <p>A <strong>standard devia=
tion</strong> (or =CF=83) is a measure of how dispersed the data is in rela=
tion to the mean. Low, or small, standard deviation indicates data are clus=
tered tightly around the mean, and high, or large, standard deviation indic=
ates data are more spread out. A standard deviation close to zero indicates=
 that data points are very close to the mean, whereas a larger standard dev=
iation indicates data points are spread further away from the mean.</p>
												=09
												<p>In the image, the curve on top is more spread out and theref=
ore has a higher standard deviation, while the curve below is more clustere=
d around the mean and therefore has a lower standard deviation.<sup><a href=
=3D"https://www.nlm.nih.gov/oet/ed/stats/02-900.html#fn1" id=3D"anch_1">1</=
a></sup></p>
												 </div>
												=09
												<div class=3D"col-md-5 mx-auto text-center">
                                                    <div class=3D"graphic">
                                                        <a href=3D"https://=
www.nlm.nih.gov/oet/ed/stats/img/StandardDeviation.png" target=3D"_blank"><=
img class=3D"img-fluid" src=3D"https://www.nlm.nih.gov/oet/ed/stats/img/Sta=
ndardDeviation.png" alt=3D"A graphic showing high and low standard deviatio=
n curves."></a>
                                                    </div>
													<div class=3D"text-center">
													<p>
														<em><small>Example Standard Deviation Curves</small></em>
													</p>
												   </div>
												=09
												</div>
												=09
												<div class=3D"col-lg-12">
												=09
												<p>To calculate the standard deviation, use the following formu=
la:</p>
												=09
												 </div>
												=09
												<div class=3D"col-md-4">
                                                    <div class=3D"graphic">
                                                        <a href=3D"https://=
www.nlm.nih.gov/oet/ed/stats/img/SDFormula.png" target=3D"_blank"><img clas=
s=3D"img-fluid" src=3D"https://www.nlm.nih.gov/oet/ed/stats/img/SDFormula.p=
ng" alt=3D"In this formula, =CF=83 is the standard deviation, x1 is the dat=
a point we are solving for in the set, =C2=B5 is the mean, and N is the tot=
al number of data points."></a>
                                                    </div>
											=09
												=09
												</div>
												<br>
											=09
												<div class=3D"col-lg-12">
												=09
												<p>In this formula, =CF=83 is the standard deviation, x<sub>i</=
sub> is each individual data point in the set, =C2=B5 is the mean, and N is=
 the total number of data points. In the equation, x<sub>i</sub>, represent=
s each individual data point, so if you have 10 data points, subtract x<sub=
>1</sub> (first data point) from the mean and then square the absolute valu=
e. This process is continued all the way through x<sub>10</sub> (last data =
point). The results are then summed (symbolized as =CE=A3), which is the nu=
merator of the fraction from the equation.</p>
												=09
												<p>Let=E2=80=99s go back to the class example, but this time lo=
ok at their height. To calculate the standard deviation of the class=E2=80=
=99s heights, first calculate the mean from each individual height. In this=
 class, there are nine students with an average height of 75 inches. Now th=
e standard deviation equation looks like this:</p>
												 </div>
												=09
												<div class=3D"col-md-4">
                                                    <div class=3D"graphic">
                                                        <a href=3D"https://=
www.nlm.nih.gov/oet/ed/stats/img/SDFormulaEx.png" target=3D"_blank"><img cl=
ass=3D"img-fluid" src=3D"https://www.nlm.nih.gov/oet/ed/stats/img/SDFormula=
Ex.png" alt=3D"To calculate the standard deviation of the class=E2=80=99s h=
eights, first calculate the mean from each individual height. In this class=
 there are nine students with an average height of 75 inches."></a>
                                                    </div>
											=09
												=09
												</div>
												=20
												<br>
											=09
												<div class=3D"col-lg-12">
												=09
												<p>The first step is to subtract the mean from each data point.=
 Then square the value before adding them all together. Now divide by 9 (th=
e total number of data points) and finally take the square root to reach th=
e standard deviation of the data:</p>
												=09
												<table class=3D"table table-bordered">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th scope=3D"col" style=3D"text-align: center">Height in inches<br> <em>x<s=
ub>i</sub></em></th>
<th scope=3D"col" style=3D"text-align: center">Mean<br> =C2=B5</th>
<th scope=3D"col" style=3D"text-align: center">Subtract mean from each data=
 point<br><em>x</em> - =C2=B5</th>
<th scope=3D"col" style=3D"text-align: center">Result<br><em>x</em></th>
<th scope=3D"col" style=3D"text-align: center">Square each value<br><em>x<s=
up>2</sup></em></th>
<th scope=3D"col" style=3D"text-align: center">Sum of Squares<br>=E2=88=91 =
<sup>x</sup></th>
<th scope=3D"col" style=3D"text-align: center">Variance<br><span style=3D"t=
ext-decoration: underline;"><em>x</em></span><br>=CE=9D</th>
<th scope=3D"col" style=3D"text-align: center">Standard Deviation<br> =CF=
=83=3D=E2=88=9A<em>x</em></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>56</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align: top;" rowspan=3D"9">75</td>
<td>56 =E2=80=93 75</td>
<td>-19</td>
<td>361</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align: top;" rowspan=3D"9">784</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align: top;" rowspan=3D"9">87.1</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align: top;" rowspan=3D"9"><strong>9.3</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>65</td>
<td>65 =E2=80=93 75</td>
<td>-10</td>
<td>100</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>74</td>
<td>74 =E2=80=93 75</td>
<td>-1</td>
<td>1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>75</td>
<td>75 =E2=80=93 75</td>
<td>0</td>
<td>0</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>76</td>
<td>76 =E2=80=93 75</td>
<td>1</td>
<td>1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>77</td>
<td>77 =E2=80=93 75&nbsp;</td>
<td>2</td>
<td>4</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>80</td>
<td>80 =E2=80=93 75</td>
<td>5</td>
<td>25</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>81</td>
<td>81 =E2=80=93 75</td>
<td>6</td>
<td>36</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>91</td>
<td>91 =E2=80=93 75</td>
<td>16</td>
<td>256</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
												=09
												<p>This data shows that 68% of heights were 75 inches plus or m=
inus 9.3 inches (1 standard deviation away from the mean), 95% of heights w=
ere 75=E2=80=99=E2=80=99 plus or minus 18.6=E2=80=99=E2=80=99 (2 standard d=
eviations away from the mean), and 99.7% of heights were 75=E2=80=99=E2=80=
=99 plus or minus 27.9=E2=80=99=E2=80=99 (3 standard deviations away from t=
he mean).</p>
												=09
												<hr>
												<p class=3D"small">
